The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", published a brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso share several common traits.
They belong to the older generation, they are not able to engage in work for health reasons, they are free and have no children.
The one who becomes a witch is sent to isolation so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"This fate is very seldom attained."
“Young healthy women don’t give up, either, because they help at work and give birth to children,” describes a nun who is taking care of more than a hundred women in a special house in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, which their community has expelled from its ranks.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She has published an information booklet to help limit witch hunts.
It has a hook.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," Die Standard newspaper noted.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
In Ghana, which is neighbouring Burkina Faso, Amma Hemma, 72, died last week after three women and two men tortured her, poured petroleum and set her on fire.
The BBC reported on the case.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, the woman was burned with oil, which is used for ritual anointing.
It was reported that he had been fired after the group wanted to “expel the evil spirit” from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a forty-two-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “Devouring human souls has always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to mitigate the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president himself participated.
“After the death of his aunt, Gambian President Jammi launched a massive hunt for witches who were supposed to be involved in her death and try to use black magic to kill the president himself.”
“He called on shamans from nearby Guinea to help him, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president’s personal security, were forcibly taking randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in a statement.
At the farm, prisoners had to drink herbal spirits with hallucinogenic effects, which in addition caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two prisoners did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were released.
