The offices also include a kindergarten, the architects understood.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect to also hide a mini-school with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a pile of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Design employees can visit it.
The design and architecture company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings were built, has been counting on space for its corporate mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs nearly 90 people, mostly of baby boom age, and it was important for women designers and architects to be able to return to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of short-term work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of the social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine demanding jobs with childcare.
The mini-school was invented by Arch.Design employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-school is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the grant funding (subsidy of CZK 2, 8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and to provide qualified personnel and operations for two years.
After the financial grant (2 years) has been exhausted, Arch.Design is obliged to operate a mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year and the request for a grant was greatly aided by the company Economy Rating.
Care is provided by qualified staff, the children are taken care of all day by a nurse and a teacher of the school, so children can go to kindergarten without age restriction, but most of them are older than 3 years.
Since it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day there are even more.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of positions in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program fill in the undergraduate school is comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
Not only do children play here, but they are also provided with quality instruction - from basic knowledge to preparation for school benches, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and eliminate stressful situations with delayed picking up children from kindergartens away from their parents’ workplace.
Parents can make more productive use of their working hours.
It is not surprising that an employee-employer relationship is naturally formed here.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personal marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of an ancient lizard, the staircase resembles the back of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
Such is the house Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all typical of the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudí.
The front of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
With detailed observation, geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order can be seen.
At night, the entire facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the glow of colors is further enhanced.
Winding and twisting of shapes to the same extent appears in interiors.
Wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of the door, cuckoo and railings.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gràcia 43, was built in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building an entirely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batlló, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated with him.
It was on his design board that decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
A number of other artists and artists have also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the Casa Batlló project started with the successful collaboration between Jujol and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and Güell Park, which contains other Gaudí's works.
From the locals, the house immediately after completion earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it the "home of the living room".
It is also said that on the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí in the house designed for his time a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree slope.
In his work, Gaudí absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he received a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when the city council was completed, it was confounded and asked for repairs.
For example, councillors were troubled by the fact that the building interfered with the pillars and the public pavement.
There has never been a remedy, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the call of the city district, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a communal lounge and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house crosses the stairs, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The fundamental elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the living room doors and a larger company can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí’s reconstruction also acquired unconventional roofing and two additional floors.
Gaudí’s play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, with which the inner courtyard is lined, and lanterns, is also impressive.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Batlló, which was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and the most profitable apartment made available to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftyth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
The tours continued as they found it to be a very advantageous undertaking and in addition they extended the tours to common areas and lofts, including a roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is certainly not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum significantly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of a house with dragon towers, you need to quickly scramble with one of the inhabitants of the zinják and visit him directly at home.
How to choose a mattress and a grid: women have different requirements than men
Not the glorious frame of the bed, but the quality of the laying area, that is, the mattress and the grid, give the foundation of a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously complemented to suit a specific user.
When choosing, it decides a lot of things, from weight, height, age, health condition and sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and grid are made is also important.
A typical example?
For example, for weekend cottages, where they do not sink regularly, latex mattresses are not suitable, because they "heat" more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than standard polyurethane mattresses.
In this case, it is necessary to rotate them regularly.
Because if they do not have a lot of air ducts in the core, and they are still lying on a hard plate, they retain moisture: mold could also appear under them.
The choice also depends on the habit.
Those who have spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
"Maybe all the hockey players who came back from the NHL were complaining about not sleeping here."
"On their bent shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam."
"These are also recommended for people with diabetes who have a disorder of the nervous system, so they do not absorb "information" from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
For many hockey players, but also for other customers, she was looking for a mattress with linen foam years ago.
"Today it's okay, suitable mattresses have Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don't have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape according to the absorbed heat or adapts to your warm body.
Nothing pushes you, you will not turn around at night like after a hard fight.
You'll just get a better night's sleep.
Lazy foam also serves as a protection against diarrhea.
When choosing the size of the mattress to your height, add the length of the foot, which is about 21 to 34 cm.
A man and a woman with a height of about 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for double beds, thus a total of 180 cm.
For single beds, for example, singles, at least 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For convenience and a possible visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly folded in the elbow," advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, technician of the Department of Pads and Decorators, who is already working on the issue of healthy sleep and ergonomics of the wreath.
For a double bed, everyone needs their own grid and mattress, but here, be careful when buying to adjust the height of the mattress.
Otherwise, there will be nothing but to mount the grids to different heights, but you may not be able to do this at every frame of the bed.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, types with a spring skeleton at least 15, of which at least three centimeters count on the forming and crucible layer.
"When you touch your hands or get stuck on a mattress, you definitely can't feel the springs," Helena Prokopová warns.
Each mattress requires a certain type of grid.
The upholstered beds, where the mattress and mattress are like siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
The mattresses are poorly ventilated, it is not possible to wash their cover, which is already common today.
And since we usually sweat out 0.2 to 0.75 liters of sweat per night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will start to resemble one large (and clogged) mesh.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about the lifespan of mattresses up to 25 years, or even lifetime guarantees.
But everything has its buts.
And so the advice from the dealers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm of hygiene and work, do not give up the removable coating, but rather add a mattress protector, which you can easily remove and wash.
Although mattress coatings are commonly produced throughout the circuit, so after unlocking we get two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine very important!), nevertheless, handling in larger types (and in one person) when shooting could resemble a lightweight wrestling in the ring.
Do you have a hardboard in your bed?
Never! Never!
Maximum for a bed intended for one night visits.
However, if you don’t already have any air holes on the board, use a mattress with a spring skeleton and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (including Taschenfederkern) and a chip layer.
Polyurethane mattress does not belong to such a substrate.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (e.g., a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable for non-layering lamella grilles with 14 to 18 lamellae, but you will always pay for grilles with more lamellae, 28 or more, where the lamellae in the hips are doubled and their stiffness can be adjusted.
The positioning lamella gratings do not include mattresses with a spring skeleton, because they do not react to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the slats, the so-called shoulder cradle can also be used.
It is a special slat fitting that allows you to push, or even tilt the slat so that the sleeping arm is nicely "punched".
For men who have "shoulders over the whole back", definitely an important thing.
Even the manufacturers of mattresses, who in the "men's" began to use the softening zone in the shoulder area, remember it already.
They also remember women - they in turn give them a softer surface in the places of the hips.
For the most demanding customers, wing or plate gratings with so-called multi-torsion bracing are designed.
The pressure breaks down to several points and the voltage decreases.
However, be careful, once you use the right mattress and grill the wrong pillow (large and "charged"), most of the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the tips should only touch the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can be relaxed.
As a suitable size it is recommended 50 x 60 cm, which they prefer, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should equal the height of the shoulder (along with the shoulder cradle or a softened zone in the mattress).
