Human-monitoring devices want more and more parents, they want to take care of their children
Fear of one’s own child brings more and more people to the idea of GPS surveillance.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also track the movement of people, and thus help in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anika Janatková.
The device is now about the size of a box of syrups, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
A number of people were frightened by the case of the missing Anika and began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage, but another means of reducing the likelihood that a tragedy will happen,” says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices may be misused, for example when they are put in the bag of someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Mostly customers actually buy it for safety reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in case of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková points out that if a child does not want to wear something similar, he will simply get rid of it.
“Even very young children show great creativity in how to intentionally lose some things when they don’t want to be under control.”
"A lot of expectations have been raised by parents in the past, but mobile phones can be turned off just like these tracking devices," says Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková.
It is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"When it comes to a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will almost always ensure that the child does not have any electronics that could reveal his or her location."
"Now it's a phone."
“When they start expanding their tracking devices, they’ll be looking for them, because their sales will certainly be supported by massive advertising.”
“In such a case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert <0xC4><0x8C>ech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after the attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to send a position regularly after a certain period of time."
