A longer index than a ring indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than a ring are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60 years of age,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick’s Institute for Cancer Research.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly in combination with genetic risk or other risk factors, such as family health stress, Eeles said.
In the period 1994-2009, colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and more than 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
More than half of the study participants had a shorter pointer on their right hand than a ring.
They had the same chance of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those who had an index finger longer than a ring, this risk decreased by 33 percent, for men under sixty, it decreased by even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer indicator.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that promotes growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences Professor Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es told <0xC4><0x8C>TK that he knew about this study, but did not think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer was "completely proven".
