The support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the support for private entrepreneurship.
Criminal activity is more worrying than unemployment.
And Brazil considers many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of a recent Latinobarómetro survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
This year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, dominates two related issues.
The first is that Latin America has a pretty cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy recovered after a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are Democrats in their beliefs, bringing down the regional average (see Chart 2).
Around 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, this is a large increase (Figure 3).
Around 34% said they trust the House in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis in Latin America undermined democracy.
Support emerged during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and dropped again to 32% this year.)
However, the mood varies in a wide range from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its resigning president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
