Prosecutors at the Justice Department cleared Senator John Ensign of a criminal charge related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure a lobby, lawyers told the senator on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican, faced and who, until the time of the scandal, was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, his affair getting into national headlines and damaging his career.
Mr Ensign’s office said he was “certainly pleased” with the decision that followed nearly a year of investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary proceedings at the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department "informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the target of the investigation and that he has no plans to bring further charges against him in this matter."
The Ministry of Justice declined to comment on the case.
The decision was a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Department of Justice who argued that there was serious evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing a violation of the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents published in October 2009 in the New York Times reported that Mr. Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobby that was supposed to lead to Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, being silent about the senator's relationship with her.
Mrs. Hampton used to work as a treasurer in the Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign has contacted a number of political supporters to find a job for Mr. Hampton and to support their views after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, so much so that the documents and interviews state.
Since Hampton was until recently Mr. Ensign's assistant, he was barred from lobbying his former employer or Senate for a year.
Ethics experts claim that the unusual settlement of Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared in conflict with the ban on lobbying.
From the evidence released, "it turned out that this is a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients who are being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasons for the decision in Senator Ensign's case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the ministry is cautious about political lawsuits after a large number of failures, including a decision by Steve to suspend the lawsuit last year.
Federal prosecutors “clearly concealed the weapons,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a law group that filed several complaints against Mr Ensign in the case.
"This basically indicates that high-ranking government officials are not subject to the laws," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s chief lawyer, said he was called by the Attorney General of the Department of Justice on Monday and then the next day, and told him that the Department found no charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defense team is working with prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had submitted to the public prosecutors.
"I am not pleased to portray the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice except that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Electoral Commission decided to stop investigating a separate complaint in which the ethics group alleges that the payment of Ensign Hampton’s parents in the amount of $96,000 violated the federal electoral law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money meant nothing but a gift.
One company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find a lobbying job was NV Energy, the main Nevada company that had long supported the senator.
