U.S. document reveals Moscow as a haven of corruption
The management of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy” and this continues to be part of the bribes and protection bribes coming on its way to the Kremlin, the US embassy in Russia said in a February tape.
Both the police and the Federal Security Service are largely holding protective wings that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They collect money not only from legal businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – which Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertices of the office” – will take its own when the money starts to move up the ladder.
The record, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published on Wednesday via WikiLeaks on their website.
The record is based on the sources whose names have been edited.
The record was written at a time when Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor and accuses him of a large share of corruption.
It was recalled in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but since then we can only see minimal changes in the cleanliness.
Luzhkov and his wife Yelena Baturina, who owns a prominent construction company, have consistently denied corruption charges for many years, and have won several lawsuits on false charges for such allegations.
In September, he told the Russian TV station when asked about proven evidence of corruption: "It's crazy, it's dirt, it's shit."
The Russians believe with absolute conviction that if their society is corrupted, it will turn out to be a vote.
It is unusual, however, to encounter such details in such a way, in the embassy report, and it is also unheard of for diplomats from foreign countries to do so.
“Moscow’s city government and its connection to criminal elements have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional,’ and confirm that the government operates more as a kleptocracy than as a government,” the report says.
"Criminal elements enjoy the so-called 'krysha' (a term from the world of crime and the mafia, which literally means 'roof' or protection), provided by the police, the Federal Security Service, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior and the Office of the Prosecutor, as well as everywhere in the government bureaucracy.
Analysts have also identified a three-stage structure in Moscow’s criminal world.
"Luzhkov is at the very top."
"The Federal Security Service, the Department of the Interior and the militia are in the second grade."
"And finally, at the lowest level, there are ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors."
“It’s an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill vacancies in some areas because the city doesn’t provide some services.”
The report says the FSB is taking money from the largest companies and the police are targeting smaller companies.
One source said, "Owners of stores in Moscow realize that it is better to get protection from the FSB or the Ministry of the Interior (rather than from organized criminal groups), as they not only have more weapons, resources and strength than criminal groups, but they are also protected by law."
"For this reason, protection from criminal gangs is no longer in the pipeline."
The record says that while the withdrawal of money is complex, the protection itself can already have trouble; even those who pay can sometimes be arrested.
For those who do not pay quickly enough, their shops are closed under various pretexts.
