Veterans of the Khmer Rouge are forced to deal with the past
In a heavily lit concrete classroom with dirty and peeled walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School recalled the man who built it, the leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Moka."
"He was a good leader and took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as a "slaughterman" for his cruelty during the Khmer Rouge government, the commander in this remote Khmer Rouge country in northwest Cambodia remains popular, where he has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered, long-standing loyalty is broken in Anlong Veng as well.
In April, the victims of the Truth and Reconciliation Forum were allowed to publicly confront people who were part of the regime.
In June, the government provided textbooks that for the first time explain the history of the Khmer Rouge and their former soldiers to children.
And in July, the United Nations and the Cambodian court will jointly issue the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, the sentencing of a former leader, the notorious violent association Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Spirit, to 35 years in prison.
With each such progress, unrest has grown among Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng, making efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society more complicated.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia's documentation centre, an independent organization investigating the regime.
"For them, life among the Khmer Rouge was wonderful, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its troops fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary led guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated supporters in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement, the country was led to the first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to transition to a government that culminated in the capitulation of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural death in 1998 and Ta Mok, who survived, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh Prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters fell into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically remember the time of the movement.
Although several elite Khmer Rouges have maintained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak as unskilled farmers.
"These people had only minimal benefit from capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which is run by public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are surrounded by the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They were educated without any idea of doing business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling down as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"The Mok has nourished them all."
"But now life is hard, because we have to take care of everything ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge court has also raised concerns.
Early next year, the court will begin investigating Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court has a mandate to prosecute the leader and the people responsible for the crimes, but it has not been said whether it will continue in these four cases.
It was not enough to calm the worries in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a regional leader in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge government in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Documentation Center in Cambodia that she was overseeing the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project that likely killed thousands of forced workers.
On a recent steamy evening, Im Chaem returned from work on the field to her wooden cottage on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun began to set and shadows appeared over the flat grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about her past among the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to go.
"There is peace and stability in Cambodia," she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who ran away from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also repeatedly warned that there would be instability if the court searched for more suspects, although experts and historians disagree.
"Cambodia must dig a deep hole and bury the past in it," he said.
But confronting the past is just what Cambodia has to do to move forward, Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center said.
"Reconciliation in Khmer conditions means colliding broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand each other."
The Centre has published the first textbook approved by the Khmer Rouge government, has 75 pages and is titled "History of Democratic Cambodia."
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as an addendum to the Ministry of Education's history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
Like many people in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng knew little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the connection of the city with the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a high school student in Anlong Veng, said the new textbook helps students understand important parts of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he took home the book for study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the courts," he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people the court will sue."
Such resistance makes the process of reconciliation more complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, textbooks and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a strong charm here.
At the top of the Dangrek Mountains, the road is covered with weeds and sprinkled with discarded plastic bags, leading to a rectangle made of black suede, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a mobile phone saleswoman on the side of the road, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated at the spot.
"But he has a strong spirit, a lot of locals come here and pray to him," she said.
Nuom Sothea had a birthday and planned to visit Pol Pot's resting place later, where she would bring a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope that it would bring her luck.
