Sport and circumvention of rules
The Finty, as shown by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax, show cleverness rather than the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramose) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be drawn about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behavior and whether UEFA should not have both footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which had their team clearly won), the appointed players deliberately lost time one after another at the time when the foul was to be played to provoke the judge, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in his group in the lead - and will be able, deprived of cards, to proceed to the next phase.
In the end, the UEFA disciplinary committee fined coach José Mourinho for two games and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so prevalent that it is part of the ethos of football, i.e. rules that are unwritten but watched.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that the participant was the Real Madrid team (who boasts in his anthem of nobility and honor, and who has already fined his players for similar acts), and as it seems, also thanks to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds to his long history of comedy.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of action, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether circumvention of the law occurs in these acts; it is indeed an action respecting the rules of sport, the meaning of which, however, it seems, is to be circumvented.
It is a question of what kind of damage such actions cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the characteristics of sports behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which in these cases has not been violated, or there has not been a violent game.
Another of these characteristics of pure play is to avoid giving players an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which did not happen here either.
Thus, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as cheating or circumvention of the law has not occurred, there has not been a covert violation of the rules in order to avoid the penalty, but this behavior should be as obvious as possible in order to receive the penalty.
They waited and liked to be punished.
The next question, however, is what benefit the perpetrators will have from their intentional offense.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that he does not make any profit in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, that is, at first glance the team can be eliminated, and besides this action the players will be relieved of the penalty, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which the exclusion is enough one card less than in the first round.
So how the wheels will continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, part of which is to make strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case that we deal with here, the players did not aim to avoid the imposition of a penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without evading or fleeing punishment.
Although the boundary between cleverness and circumvention of rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly cleverness.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because they were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which instructions were transmitted to provoke them from the leadership.
The damage to sporting principles by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
