The U.S. is changing its visa rules.
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centers before the Consular Department interview; costs will be lower and waiting time will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
with the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres (abbreviated from ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC personnel will collect the biometric information of the applicant and they will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain benefits, including the following:
The total cost of obtaining a visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for arranging a meeting, second for processing the application and others for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant will only pay a single fee to cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 per tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for business and investor visas.
People who want to renew their visa will not need to have an interview with a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview meeting at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an additional $26 service fee.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for a visa, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA Announces Discovery of Extraterrestrial Life
The U.S. Space Agency convened a press conference tomorrow to present a discovery that could cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life.
The U.S. National Aviation and Space Administration (NASA) is announcing an astrobiological discovery Thursday that could confirm the theory of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. by experts in astrobiology, a science that deals with the study of the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in space, at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington.
Inviting journalists, NASA assured that it would present a "discovery that will cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life", prompting speculation by experts from other countries.
The discovery could confirm the theory that there are other creatures besides us, living in inhospitable conditions that were considered uninhabitable, and that could present the possibility that one day they will become intelligent creatures, such as humans, if the conditions in which they live improve.
It appears to be a microbe that was found at the bottom of Lake Mono in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too toxic for any form of life, as the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow uses arsenic for its life, and it is this ability that increases the likelihood that similar life could exist on other planets that do not have the atmosphere that is on Earth.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be proved that “there is another, different form of life than the one we know.”
The space agency will announce the real extent of the discoveries at tomorrow's press conference.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists exploring Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) with the prospect that its chemical composition is similar to that on Earth.
