World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The United Nations today proposed in Cancun a plan to rebuild home lighting, retail lighting and industrial spaces in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse effect (GES) limit that corresponds to nearly one-third of the additional limit that needs to be achieved to stabilize the planet’s climate from now on.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to implement in Cancun to compensate for the lack of hard-to-reach reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market, are replaced by fluorescent bulbs or, even better, by bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of 1.8 billion tons would be added to the planet.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world’s emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of the global car fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, were involved in voluntary plans to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But another 5 Gt will need to be deducted from this balance in order to achieve a 2 degrees Celsius climate warming stabilisation by 2020 so that it can be excluded from getting out of control.
In heated bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, we will reduce this consumption by two more times.
Fluo-compact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, which he introduced this week to Philips' production - the company reportedly participated in a UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than the incandescent bulb, giving us an idea of the possible savings with a replacement plan that would apply in 100.
All these new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and should be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection centres.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluorescent bulb, but rather thermal coal-fired power plants that emit much of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in heated bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants release 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report also details the profits that each country would make from this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year for the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost 2.5 billion to build.
