Climate: How France Hacked Its Promises of Financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to keep the promises of fast-start funding (so-called fast-start funding or early funding) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been revealed
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (420 million euros per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU pulled out a big axe to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report clarifying the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operation invaluable and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to be treated equally and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, leading it on the right track to deliver on its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we will find that things are much more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is realised without prejudice to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding has been retained and it is adding 150 million to it for three years under the title of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
France, on the other hand, considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure from previous periods or to the global level of public aid for the development of Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), it is expected to meet its commitment to finance "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, think that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed equals 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be proven for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission reductions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we get as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , but we should not take it from the title of our equities.
But France can only justify this: it "maintains" its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million, of which 91.5% is a loan (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>389.8 million) and 8.5% is a gift (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the EU that uses a loan on this scale.
Germany asked for 46% of donations, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) respected their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, if an absolute majority of the European Union gives 1 euro to fulfil its promise, it gives France only 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
What a cute piece of jellyfish!
To sum up, in its financing of the “fast start”, France operates with a double shading: on the one hand with the development of the stock in time and on the other hand with the real financial burden.
Although it spends only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it can convince that it is spending <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
Manipulation of the Treasury Minister (because it seems that although Bercy made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and in negotiation, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is only a small issue, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate debates.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounts for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of decency and fairness towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing long-term financing contributions (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): let’s not avoid the question of “additionality” or how to book loans.
France should change its stance to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting hope in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will come to Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France’s fast-start and its vision of “additionality” and use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international trust necessary to move forward in the discussions.
